window.docContents[41].resolve({"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals--The-Ring-of-Integers-Is-a-Dedekind-Domain":{"contents":"The ring of integers  of any number field  is a Dedekind domain.\n\nmathlib's IsIntegralClosure.isDedekindDomain verifies the three defining properties\n() for the integral closure  of a Dedekind domain  in a\nfinite separable extension  of ; the number-field case is , , . The closure is integrally closed by transitivity\nof integral closures (IsIntegralClosure.isIntegrallyClosed); it is a finite -module,\nhence Noetherian, because the trace form is nondegenerate over the separable extension\n(, IsIntegralClosure.finite); and every nonzero prime of  is\nmaximal because  is integral over the dimension-one domain \n(IsIntegralClosure.isMaximal_of_isMaximal_comap together with the going-up property), so\n is a field.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory\u0009Dedekind domains and unique factorisation of ideals","header":"3.2.2. The Ring of Integers Is a Dedekind Domain","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Dedekind-domains-and-unique-factorisation-of-ideals--The-Ring-of-Integers-Is-a-Dedekind-Domain"}});